Where front-end dev fits in with
- See where web apps and front-end development fit in
- Learn what awaits you in industry
- Knowing best practices for building websites, structuring code, etc., is important for teamwork
- Most front-end developers will use modern frameworks instead of writing HTML, CSS, and JS from scratch. However,
learning the basics was necessary so that you know what the framework is doing for you underneath the hood
- Keep improving skills and gain experience. Coding is just like learning anything else: more coding == more improvement
How the above relates to using
- The front-end interacts with the back-end to transfer data and allow users to interact with the application
- On top of looking good, websites also need to display and work with data in useful, efficient ways
- The focus now is on creating functional applications that actually do things with real data
- This material is what the software industry's interviews are infamous for.
- The ability to solve problems efficiently, with the least resources, is a key skill that separates "engineers" from "coders."
- Practice, practice, practice. Just learning a concept is easier than actually applying it to a real problem. Most importantly, be patient. This stuff is hard.
- Rather than trying to memorize everything, these are "tools" in your toolbox. What's more important is intelligently reasoning through problems.
- Front-end developers aren't grilled as hard on these topics. But the more you know, the better. Starred items are the most likely to be asked in interviews.

Cloud Services, Platforms as a Service (PaaS)
- These last concepts are often learned on the job, but can be learned beforehand to prep for interviews.
- Most entry-level engineers aren't expected to be knowledgeable about these topics, but learning them can
impress interviewers and greatly help you do your job well. If you can, learn some of these in internships.
- Some companies might ask about certain concepts anyway - those are starred.
Beyond Entry-Level at Most Companies, Some Prestigious Companies
At this point you would be qualified for:
- Internships at most companies, maybe except prestigious ones
Again, it is suggested to review some of the problem solving materials in the
Algorithms & Data Structures section. The deal-breaker items are starred.
The practical experience is valuable because it's very different than solo hobby
development and putting together your own apps. Mentorship is invaluable.
Your chances of getting a full-time job are much, much better if you have internships
or previous tech-related jobs on your resume. And because it's tech, you're paid
fairly well anyway. Some software interns earn $25/hr or more (do research).
Depending on the company, you might even be able to secure a full-time position.
But it's not as likely, because most employers will ask you algorithms and data
structures questions, which are in the next section.
At this point, you would be fully qualified to work as an entry-level engineer
at most, if not all, software companies.
In our opinion, it's totally worthwhile to get a job, start earning a good salary,
and continue learning on the side even if your ultimate goal is something else
We're working on generating roadmaps for other specific "paths," but in the meantime,
we maintain an opinionated stance that either front-end, back-end, or full-stack
courses are useful for everyone no matter where you want to end up in industry.

At this point, you'd probably qualify for beyond entry-level positions, although
most people expect you to have experience as a Jr. engineer before you
apply to more senior positions. Hurry up and get a job ;)
If you're still not able to get a job with all of this knowledge, there could be a few problems:
- You maybe don't know material as well as you think.
- There might be an issue with the way you are interviewing/answering questions.
- The companies you're applying for suck and are toxic. Pretty sure most software
engineers don't know ALL of the items on this roadmap.
